            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is Heron’s formula?</h2>
              <p>
                Heron’s formula (sometimes called Hero’s formula) gives the area
                of a triangle when you know the lengths of all three sides,
                without needing the height.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Step 1: Compute the semi‑perimeter
                </p>
                <p>\( s = \dfrac{a + b + c}{2} \)</p>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">
                  Step 2: Apply Heron’s formula
                </p>
                <p>\( A = \sqrt{s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c)} \)</p>
              </div>

              <p>Here:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>\(a, b, c\) are the side lengths of the triangle</li>
                <li>\(s\) is the semi‑perimeter (half the perimeter)</li>
                <li>\(A\) is the area of the triangle</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to use the Heron’s formula calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Select an optional unit (cm, m, in, ft) or leave it blank for
                  generic units.
                </li>
                <li>Enter the three side lengths \(a\), \(b\), and \(c\).</li>
                <li>Click <strong>Calculate area</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  Read off the semi‑perimeter \(s\), the area \(A\), and the
                  triangle type (scalene, isosceles, or equilateral).
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                If the side lengths do not satisfy the triangle inequality, the
                tool will warn you that no valid triangle exists.
              </p>

              <h2>Triangle inequality check</h2>
              <p>
                Three lengths form a valid triangle only if all of the following
                are true:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>\(a + b &gt; c\)</li>
                <li>\(a + c &gt; b\)</li>
                <li>\(b + c &gt; a\)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If any of these fail (for example \(a + b \le c\)), the points
                lie on a straight line or cannot meet, so the area is zero and
                Heron’s formula is not applicable.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked examples</h2>

              <h3>Example 1 – Scalene triangle (5, 6, 7)</h3>
              <p>Given sides \(a = 5\), \(b = 6\), \(c = 7\) (in any unit):</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Semi‑perimeter: \( s = \dfrac{5 + 6 + 7}{2} = \dfrac{18}{2} =
                  9 \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Area: \( A = \sqrt{9(9 - 5)(9 - 6)(9 - 7)} = \sqrt{9 \cdot 4
                  \cdot 3 \cdot 2} = \sqrt{216} \approx 14.697 \)
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                If the sides are in centimeters, the area is approximately
                \(14.70\ \text{cm}^2\).
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Equilateral triangle (side 10)</h3>
              <p>For an equilateral triangle with \(a = b = c = 10\):</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Semi‑perimeter: \( s = \dfrac{10 + 10 + 10}{2} = \dfrac{30}{2}
                  = 15 \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Area: \( A = \sqrt{15(15 - 10)(15 - 10)(15 - 10)} = \sqrt{15
                  \cdot 5 \cdot 5 \cdot 5} = \sqrt{1875} \approx 43.301 \)
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                This matches the well‑known equilateral triangle area formula \(
                A = \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{4}a^2 = \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{4} \cdot 10^2
                \approx 43.301 \).
              </p>

              <h2>Deriving Heron’s formula (outline)</h2>
              <p>
                One standard derivation starts from the formula for the area of
                a triangle using two sides and the included angle:
              </p>
              <p>\( A = \dfrac{1}{2}ab\sin C \)</p>
              <p>
                Using the Law of Cosines, \( c^2 = a^2 + b^2 - 2ab\cos C \), you
                can express \(\cos C\) (and then \(\sin C\)) in terms of the
                side lengths \(a, b, c\). After algebraic manipulation and
                substituting into the area formula, the expression simplifies
                to:
              </p>
              <p>\( A^2 = s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c) \)</p>
              <p>
                Taking the square root of both sides gives Heron’s formula: \( A
                = \sqrt{s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c)} \).
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Does Heron’s formula work for right triangles?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. For a right triangle with legs \(a\) and \(b\) and
                hypotenuse \(c\), Heron’s formula gives the same result as \( A
                = \dfrac{1}{2}ab \).
              </p>

              <h3>What units does the area use?</h3>
              <p>
                If the sides are in centimeters, the area is in square
                centimeters (\(\text{cm}^2\)); if in meters, the area is in
                square meters (\(\text{m}^2\)); and so on. Always keep all three
                side lengths in the same unit.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can Heron’s formula give a negative value under the square root?
              </h3>
              <p>
                For a valid triangle, the expression \(s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c)\)
                is always non‑negative. If it becomes negative in numerical
                computation, it usually means the side lengths do not form a
                valid triangle or there is rounding error. This calculator
                checks the triangle inequality to avoid that issue.
              </p>
